= Editing Notes =

One of the features in normal music is that there are minute variations. This is because the music is performed by a human artist. In computer generated music the quality is not present, but LMMS offer a method to achieve it.
Just below the editor area in the piano-roll, you will find a section with vertical bars. One bar for each note in the piano-roll. Each bar represent one notes volume. 
There are 2 different ways to adjust the volume. Rest your mouse over a note and scroll the mouse-wheel. The color-brightness change. The dimmer the lower.
Of cause you also adjust each bar with your mouse and also drag the mouse along creating a wavy pattern. Especially percussion tracks can be improved with fine adjustments of the loudness.


== Copy and paste ==

When you compose you will often find the need for duplicating a selected section or all the notes in the piano-roll. LMMS offers several ways to achieve this.
All notes can be standard selected with CTRL+a
Selections can be made by:
* using the select-tool
* using keyboard-shortcuts
The select-tool in the speedbar works like a standard ‘rubber-frame’. The notes you touch with the frame will be selected. This is ok, but you will most often just like to use the keyboard-short CTRL+mouse-drag. This nifty method lets you select just as if you used the select-tool.
Releasing CTRL will put LMMS editor back to the default draw-mode.
Selected notes can be smart-copied: Rest your mouse on one of the selected notes. Hold SHIFT and drag the mouse to the wanted position. When you release the mouse, you will have a copy of your selected notes.
For a complete reference of LMMS’ keyboard shortcuts see [[http://lmms.sourceforge.net/wiki/index.php?title=Key_Mappings Mapping & Shortcuts]]

